revision.text:
{{italic title}}
The '''''Annales Barenses''''' is an anonymous set of [[annals]] written in the city of [[Bari]] in the late eleventh century. At the time of its composition, Bari was the chief city of the [[Byzantine Empire]] in southern Italy.<ref name=Kumper>{{citation |author=Hiram Kümper |chapter=Annales Barenses |title=Encyclopedia of the Medieval Chronicle |editor=Graeme Dunphy |accessdate=17 September 2016 |year=2012 |url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1163/2213-2139_emc_EMCSIM_00116}}.</ref>

The ''Annales Barenses'' are closely related to the chronicle of [[Lupus Protospatharius]] and the ''[[Anonymi Barensis Chronicon]]''. The ''Annales Barenses'' cover the period from the death of Pope [[Gregory the Great]] in 605 until the election of [[Peter III (archbishop of Acerenza)|Peter III]], [[Archbishop of Acerenza]], in 1102. They are at their most useful for the short period 1041–43.<ref name=Churchill>{{citation |author=William J. Churchill |title=The ''Annales Barenses'' and the ''Annales Lupi Protospatharii'': Critical Edition and Commentary |type=Ph. D. dissertation |institution=Centre for Medieval Studies, University of Toronto |year=1979 |url=http://www.billchurchill.com/Dissertation/ChurchillDissertation.pdf}}.</ref>

==Notes==
{{reflist}}

[[Category:Italian chronicles]]

{{italic title}} The '''''Chronicle of Melrose''''' is a medieval [[chronicle]] from the [[Cottonian Manuscript, Faustina]] B. ix within the [[British Museum]]. It was written by unknown authors, though evidence in the writing shows that it most likely was written by the monks at [[Melrose Abbey]]. The chronicle begins on the year 735 and ends in 1270, consisting of two separate segments.
The first part of the chronicle from the year 745 to about 1140 (the year Melrose Abbey was founded), is a compilation from the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]'' as well as other historical works written by [[Simeon of Durham]] and [[Hoveden]].
The second portion starts from 1140 until the end of the chronicle in 1270. It contains original work and is considered by [[historian]]s to be more credible than the first segment.
The chronicle is currently in the British Museum, taken away from [[Melrose, Scotland|Melrose]] possibly during the [[Scottish Reformation|Reformation]] period.
In 2014, it was discovered that the ''Chronicle'' contains the oldest independent account of the sealing of [[Magna Carta]].{{sfn|Stevenson|1270|p=999}}
==See also== *[[List of English chronicles]] *[[Cotton library]] *[[Solar eclipse of 1 May 1185]]
