'''Péter Szondi''' ({{IPA-hu|ˈpeːtɛr ˈsondi}}; May 27, 1929, [[Budapest]] – November 9, 1971, [[Berlin]]) was a celebrated literary scholar and philologist, originally from Hungary.
==Biography== Szondi's father was the Hungarian-Jewish psychiatrist and psychoanalyst [[Léopold Szondi]], who settled in Switzerland after his 1944 release after five months in [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.szondiforum.org/showdoc.php?id=481|title=The Leopold Szondi Forum|first=Leo|last=Berlips|website=www.szondiforum.org}}</ref>
In 1965, he became a Professor at the [[Free University of Berlin]], where he led the Institute for General and Comparative Literature. His fields were the [[history of literature]] and [[comparative literature]].
He committed suicide in 1971, leaving unfinished his book about the work of his friend [[Paul Celan]], who had killed himself the year before.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sup.org/books/title/?id=3504|title=Celan Studies|publisher=SUP|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref>
== Works == * ''Über eine "Freie Universität".'' Suhrkamp, 1973 * ''Die Theorie des bürgerlichen Trauerspiels im 18. Jahrhundert.'' Suhrkamp, 1973 * ''[[Paul Celan|Celan]]-Studien.'' Suhrkamp, 1972 = ''Celan Studies'', trans. [[Susan Bernofsky]] with Harvey Mendelsohn, Stanford University Press, 2003. {{ISBN|9780804744027}} * ''[[Friedrich Hölderlin|Hölderlin]]-Studien.'' Insel, 1967 * ''Satz und Gegensatz.'' Insel, 1964 * ''Der andere Pfeil.'' Insel, 1963 * ''Versuch über das Tragische.'' Insel, 1961 * ''Theorie des modernen Dramas.'' Suhrkamp, 1956 * "Hope in the Past: On Walter Benjamin", reprinted in [[Walter Benjamin|Benjamin, W.]] (trans. [[Howard Eiland]]), ''Berlin Childhood Around 1900'', 2006, Belknap Press [Harvard UP]. {{ISBN|0-674-02222-X}}
